{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "These are evident state-led attempts to capture and steer AI development.",
    "In this context, as Bareis and Katzenbach [62 p.875] point out, governments explicitly 'claim agency' in the production of AI technologies.Quite the opposite: it is a human strategy whereby a powerful minority of individuals attempt to get hold of the production of new technology to achieve their own goals.",
    "There are plenty of historical examples of such power dynamics as they intersect with and alter technological development, ranging from the development of railways championed by George Stephenson in Victorian England to the mechanization of Soviet agriculture led by Joseph Stalin in the early 1930s [54].",
    "The problem is that, in the present, we do not see these individuals.",
    "We do not see them acting and making choices that shape technological development."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "There are plenty of historical examples of such power dynamics as they intersect with and alter technological development, ranging from the development of railways championed by George Stephenson in Victorian England to the mechanization of Soviet agriculture led by Joseph Stalin in the early 1930s [54]."
  ]
